{"title_page": "Sc\u0103ri\u0219oara Cave", "text_new": "{{Infobox cave\n| name = Sc\u0103ri\u0219oara Cave\n| other_name = Sc\u0103ri\u0219oara Glacier\n| photo = Pestera Scarisoara - Sala Biserica.jpg\n| photo_width = \n| photo_caption = ''The Church''\n| map = \n| map_width = \n| map_caption = \n| map_alt = \n| location = [[G\u00e2rda de Sus]], [[Alba County]], [[Romania]]\n| coords = {{coord|46|29|23|N|22|48|35|E|region:RO|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref = \n| land_registry_number =\n| grid_ref_UK = \n| grid_ref_Ireland = \n| grid_ref = \n| depth = 105 m\n| length = 720 m\n| height_variation =\n| elevation = {{cvt|1150|m|}}<ref name=\"readersnatural\"/>\n| discovery = 1847\n| geology = [[Limestone]]\n| entrance_count = 1\n| entrance_list = \n| difficulty = \n| hazards = \n| access = Public\n| show_cave = \n| show_cave_length = \n| lighting = \n| visitors = \n| features = [[Stalactite]]s, [[stalagmite]]s, columns, parietal hangings, [[coralite]]s, speleothems\n| survey = \n| survey_format = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Sc\u0103ri\u0219oara Cave''' ({{Lang-ro|Pe\u0219tera Sc\u0103ri\u0219oara}}, {{lang-hu|Aranyosf\u0151i-j\u00e9gbarlang}}), is one of the biggest [[ice cave]]s in the [[Apuseni Mountains]] of [[Romania]], in a part of [[Carpathian Mountains|Carpathian chain]].<ref name=\"readersnatural\">{{Cite book|title=Natural Wonders of the World|publisher=Reader's Digest Association, Inc|year=1980|isbn=0-89577-087-3|editor-last=Scheffel|editor-first=Richard L.|location=United States of America|pages=339|quote=|editor-last2=Wernet|editor-first2=Susan J.|via=}}</ref> It is considered a [[show cave]] and one of the [[Seven Natural Wonders of Romania|natural wonders of Romania]]. It has also been described as a [[glacier cave]].<ref>[http://travelguideromania.com/scarisoara-ice-cave-biggest-underground-glacier-romania/ Scarisoara Ice Cave \u2013 the biggest underground glacier in Romania], Travel Guide Romania website, December 24, 2014, retrieved 17 January 2016.</ref>\n\n==History==\nFirst mentioned in 1863 by the Austrian geographer Arnold Schmidl, who made some observations and the first map of the cave,<ref name=\"Kokker\">Steve Kokker, Cathryn Kemp (2004). \n[https://books.google.com/books?id=hQJ8yHQpBGYC&pg=PA232&dq=Sc%C4%83ri%C5%9Foara+Cave&hl=cs&ei=E3i7TML1K5Ge4QbC7d3HDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Romania & Moldova''], Lonely Planet Publications, p. 232. {{ISBN|1-74104-149-X}}</ref> it was later explored by the Romanian scientist and [[speleologist]] [[Emil Racovi\u021b\u0103]] between 1921 and 1923,<ref name=\"Kokker\"/> who mentioned it and its origin in his 1927 work ''Speologia'' (Speleology). The ice cave was formed 3,500 years ago, during the glaciations, when these mountains were covered by snow and ice.<ref name=\"readersnatural\" /> The exact date when the cave was first discovered by humans is unknown.<ref name=\"Kokker\"/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Scarisoara Ice Cave - The Church 2.jpg|thumb|left|260px|Stalagmite from ''The Church''.]]\nThe cave is located at an altitude of approximately {{Cvt|1150|m|}} above sea level.<ref name=\"readersnatural\" /> It is {{Cvt|120|m|}} deep and {{Cvt|720|m|}} long.<ref name=\"readersnatural\" /> The entrance shaft, which is {{Cvt|60|m|}} in diameter and {{Cvt|50|m|}} in depth, gives access through metal stairs to a large  chamber, the Great Hall, which is approximately {{Cvt|108|m|}} long and {{Cvt|78|m|}} wide.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}} The Great Hall includes an ice cliff nearly {{Cvt|18|m|}} tall, which overlooks a pool called the Pool of Ice.<ref name=\"readersnatural\" />\n\nFrom the Great Hall, passages lead into several other named rooms: the Church, which features over 100 ice stalagmites, the Great Reservation, Coman Gallery to the left, and Little Reservation to the right. \n\nThe ice within the cave has an estimated volume of {{Convert|75,000|m3|cuyd|abbr=off}} and in some places can be as thick as {{Cvt|20|m|}}.<ref name=\"readersnatural\" /> The temperature is up to +1&nbsp;\u00b0C in the summer and down to -7&nbsp;\u00b0C in the winter. In the part for tourists the average temperature is around 0&nbsp;\u00b0C. [[Bat]]s live in the ice cave, as do small bugs (2\u20133&nbsp;mm long) called ''Pholeuon prozerpinae glaciale''. In the ''Big Reservation'' a [[Rupicapra rupicapra|Rupicapra]] skeleton was discovered.\n\n== Access ==\nThe portion of the cave open to tourists includes the entrance shaft, The Big Hall and The Church. Access to the other chambers is reserved for scientific research by the agreement of the Speological Institute of [[Cluj-Napoca]].<ref name=\"readersnatural\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of caves#Romania|List of caves]]\n* [[Apuseni Natural Park]] \n* [[Seven Natural Wonders of Romania]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.romanianmonasteries.org/romania/scarisoara-cave Scarisoara Cave] - Romanian Monasteries.org\n\n{{Seven Natural Wonders of Romania}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scarisoara Cave}}\n[[Category:Caves of Romania]]\n[[Category:Geography of Bihor County]]\n[[Category:Geography of Transylvania]]\n[[Category:Ice caves]]\n[[Category:Show caves]]\n[[Category:Western Romanian Carpathians]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Romania]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bihor County]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cave\n| name = Sc\u0103ri\u0219oara Cave\n| other_name = Sc\u0103ri\u0219oara Glacier\n| photo = Pestera Scarisoara - Sala Biserica.jpg\n| photo_width = \n| photo_caption = ''The Church''\n| map = \n| map_width = \n| map_caption = \n| map_alt = \n| location = [[G\u00e2rda de Sus]], [[Alba County]], [[Romania]]\n| coords = {{coord|46|29|23|N|22|48|35|E|region:RO|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref = \n| land_registry_number =\n| grid_ref_UK = \n| grid_ref_Ireland = \n| grid_ref = \n| depth = 105 m\n| length = 720 m\n| height_variation =\n| elevation = {{cvt|1150|m|}}<ref name=\"readersnatural\"/>\n| discovery = 1847\n| geology = [[Limestone]]\n| entrance_count = 1\n| entrance_list = \n| difficulty = \n| hazards = \n| access = Public\n| show_cave = \n| show_cave_length = \n| lighting = \n| visitors = \n| features = [[Stalactite]]s, [[stalagmite]]s, columns, parietal hangings, [[coralite]]s, speleothems\n| survey = \n| survey_format = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Sc\u0103ri\u0219oara Cave''' ({{Lang-ro|Pe\u0219tera Sc\u0103ri\u0219oara}}, {{lang-hu|Aranyosf\u0151i-j\u00e9gbarlang}}), is one of the biggest [[ice cave]]s in the [[Apuseni Mountains]] of [[Romania]], in a part of [[Carpathian Mountains|Carpathian chain]].<ref name=\"readersnatural\">{{Cite book|title=Natural Wonders of the World|publisher=Reader's Digest Association, Inc|year=1980|isbn=0-89577-087-3|editor-last=Scheffel|editor-first=Richard L.|location=United States of America|pages=339|quote=|editor-last2=Wernet|editor-first2=Susan J.|via=}}</ref> It is considered a [[show cave]] and one of the [[Seven Natural Wonders of Romania|natural wonders of Romania]]. It has also been described as a [[glacier cave]].<ref>[http://travelguideromania.com/scarisoara-ice-cave-biggest-underground-glacier-romania/ Scarisoara Ice Cave \u2013 the biggest underground glacier in Romania], Travel Guide Romania website, December 24, 2014, retrieved 17 January 2016.</ref>\n\n==History==\nFirst mentioned in 1863 by the Austrian geographer Arnold Schmidl, who made some observations and the first map of the cave,<ref name=\"Kokker\">Steve Kokker, Cathryn Kemp (2004). \n[https://books.google.com/books?id=hQJ8yHQpBGYC&pg=PA232&dq=Sc%C4%83ri%C5%9Foara+Cave&hl=cs&ei=E3i7TML1K5Ge4QbC7d3HDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Romania & Moldova''], Lonely Planet Publications, p. 232. {{ISBN|1-74104-149-X}}</ref> it was later explored by the Romanian scientist and [[speleologist]] [[Emil Racovi\u021b\u0103]] between 1921 and 1923,<ref name=\"Kokker\"/> who mentioned it and its origin in his 1927 work ''Speleology''. The ice cave was formed 3500 years ago, during the glaciations, when these mountains were covered by snow and ice.<ref name=\"readersnatural\" /> The exact date when the cave was first discovered by humans is unknown.<ref name=\"Kokker\"/>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Scarisoara Ice Cave - The Church 2.jpg|thumb|left|260px|Stalagmite from ''The Church''.]]\nThe cave is located at an altitude of approximately {{Cvt|1150|m|}} above sea level.<ref name=\"readersnatural\" /> It is {{Cvt|120|m|}} deep and {{Cvt|720|m|}} long.<ref name=\"readersnatural\" /> The entrance shaft, which is {{Cvt|60|m|}} in diameter and {{Cvt|50|m|}} in depth, gives access through metal stairs to a large  chamber, the Great Hall, which is approximately {{Cvt|108|m|}} long and {{Cvt|78|m|}} wide.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}} The Great Hall includes an ice cliff nearly {{Cvt|18|m|}} tall, which overlooks a pool called the Pool of Ice.<ref name=\"readersnatural\" />\n\nFrom the Great Hall, passages lead into several other named rooms: the Church, which features over 100 ice stalagmites, the Great Reservation, Coman Gallery to the left, and Little Reservation to the right. \n\nThe ice within the cave has an estimated volume of {{Convert|75,000|m3|cuyd|abbr=off}} and in some places can be as thick as {{Cvt|20|m|}}.<ref name=\"readersnatural\" /> The temperature is up to +1&nbsp;\u00b0C in the summer and down to -7&nbsp;\u00b0C in the winter. In the part for tourists the average temperature is around 0&nbsp;\u00b0C. [[Bat]]s live in the ice cave, as do small bugs (2\u20133&nbsp;mm long) called ''Pholeuon prozerpinae glaciale''. In the ''Big Reservation'' a [[Rupicapra rupicapra|Rupicapra]] skeleton was discovered.\n\n== Access ==\nThe portion of the cave open to tourists includes the entrance shaft, The Big Hall and The Church. Access to the other chambers is reserved for scientific research by the agreement of the Speological Institute of [[Cluj-Napoca]].